5.9.3 Define A Trigger
Lesson
Triggers are the starting point for any workflow—they determine when and how a flow begins execution. Triggers instantiate the flow based on specific conditions or events occurring within ServiceNow.

Types of Triggers
- Record-Based Triggers: Activate when a record is created, updated, or deleted. The triggering record's data can be referenced throughout the flow.

- Date-Based Triggers: Run flows on a schedule—daily, weekly, monthly, or at custom intervals. Perfect for routine maintenance or scheduled tasks.

- Application-Based Triggers: Become available when specific application spokes are activated.

Scenario
Continuing your work, you've created the "Infinity Item Request" flow in Workflow Studio. Now you need to define what will actually start this workflow. 

The IT department wants the flow to automatically begin whenever an employee submits a new item request through the Service Catalog. Your task is to configure the appropriate trigger so the workflow activates at the right moment—when a Service Catalog request is created.

Task Objectives

1. Access the Trigger configuration section within Workflow Studio. 

2. Select and configure an application-based trigger

3. Associate the Service Catalog application with your flow

4. Select Done to save the trigger. Then, select the More actions menu in Workflow Studio and select Force Save.

To begin, navigate to All > Process Automation > Workflow Studio > Infinity Item Request flow.
5.9.4 Add the First Action
Lesson
Actions are the building blocks of workflow automation—they define what the flow actually does once it's triggered. In Workflow Studio, the Actions section displays the most recent and most popular actions used across all Workflow Studio users in the last 7 days, making it easy to find commonly used operations.

ServiceNow provides several core actions that handle common automation tasks:
- Ask for Approval: Create approval requests on any record with configurable rules for approval, rejection, or cancellation, plus due dates.

- Create Record: Generate new records on any table with customizable field values.

- Delete Record: Remove records from any table.

- Update Record: Modify existing records by changing field values.
These are just a few examples of the types of actions. 

Beyond core actions, you can access application-specific actions by activating the associated spoke for that application, expanding your automation possibilities.

